## Baby Example: A Nonlinear Regression Example

To see a more dramatic comparison, consider a simulated dataset where the true relationship is clearly nonlinear.

Suppose the response is generated by:

\[
y = \sin(x) + \epsilon
\]

where \(\epsilon\) is random noise.

In this setting, **linear regression** will struggle because it tries to fit a straight line, while **BART** can adapt to the curved relationship much more effectively.

---

## Step 1: Simulate the Data

```{r}
# Load BART
library(BART)

# Set seed for reproducibility
set.seed(123)

# Simulate predictor values
x <- seq(0, 10, length.out = 200)

# Simulate nonlinear response
y <- sin(x) + rnorm(200, sd = 0.2)

# Put into a data frame for convenience
sim_data <- data.frame(x = x, y = y)

# Look at first few rows
head(sim_data)


# BART needs predictor matrix form
x_mat <- as.matrix(sim_data$x)

# Fit BART regression model
bart_model <- wbart(x.train = x_mat, y.train = sim_data$y)

# Get BART fitted values
bart_pred <- bart_model$yhat.train.mean

# Fit linear regression
lm_model <- lm(y ~ x, data = sim_data)

# Get linear regression predictions
lm_pred <- predict(lm_model)

# Compute mean squared errors
bart_mse <- mean((sim_data$y - bart_pred)^2)
lm_mse <- mean((sim_data$y - lm_pred)^2)

bart_mse
lm_mse

# Plot the observed data
plot(sim_data$x, sim_data$y,
     pch = 16,
     col = "gray",
     xlab = "x",
     ylab = "y",
     main = "BART vs Linear Regression on Nonlinear Data")

# Add BART fitted curve
lines(sim_data$x, bart_pred,
      col = "blue",
      lwd = 3)

# Add linear regression fitted line
lines(sim_data$x, lm_pred,
      col = "red",
      lwd = 3)

# Add legend
legend("topright",
       legend = c("BART", "Linear Regression"),
       col = c("blue", "red"),
       lwd = 3)
       
       

### Why this one is better
#- the visual difference is much stronger
#- BART’s curve will usually look clearly better
#- the MSE gap is often larger than in `mtcars`

### What to say
#> In this example, the true relationship is nonlinear, so #linear regression is misspecified. BART performs much better #because it can flexibly follow the shape of the data.

#If you want, I can also give you a **classification example #with more dramatic results** too.


```




